# Frontend Guidelines (WXT + React + TypeScript + Tailwind)

## Framework & Structure
- This is a WXT browser extension project
- Use React 19 with functional components and hooks
- Write all components in TypeScript (`.tsx`)
- Use Tailwind CSS v4 for styling

## Component Patterns
- Use functional components with hooks
- Keep components small and focused
- Extract reusable logic into custom hooks
- Co-locate component styles and tests

## TypeScript
- Define explicit types for props and state
- Avoid `any` - use proper types
- Use interfaces for object shapes, types for unions/primitives

## Styling with Tailwind
- Use Tailwind utility classes directly in JSX
- Only add the tailwind classes necessary - keep it simple
- Use `cn()` helper (clsx + tailwind-merge) for conditional classes
- Follow the project's shadcn/ui patterns for components

## shadcn/ui Components
- Use existing Radix UI primitives from the project
- Follow shadcn/ui patterns for new components
- Import from `@/components/ui/`

## WXT Extension Specifics
- Place entry points in appropriate WXT directories
- Use WXT's built-in APIs for extension functionality
- **Browser-Agnostic**: Use `browser.*` API (WebExtensions standard), NOT `chrome.*`
- WXT automatically polyfills `browser.*` for all supported browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Safari)
- For storage, use `browser.storage.local` instead of `chrome.storage.local`
- Import browser APIs from `wxt/browser` when type hints are needed

## Example Component
```tsx
import { cn } from "@/lib/utils"

interface MyComponentProps {
  title: string
  className?: string
}

export function MyComponent({ title, className }: MyComponentProps) {
  return (
    <div className={cn("p-4 rounded-lg", className)}>
      <h2 className="text-lg font-semibold">{title}</h2>
    </div>
  )
}
```
